<h3>The North Star: A focus on <strong>feeling good</strong></h3>
<p>
  Home screens typically bludgeon you with data&mdash;charts, graphs, percentages of something. 
  The stuff that makes for a good marketing site screenshot.
</p>
<p>
  In real life, you feel bad. Have you ever looked at a productivity chart and thought, "Wow, we're doing great"? Neither have I.
<p>
  The Home screen is also the very first screen a new customer sees after Jason's welcome message. 
  It's an opportunity to introduce not just Basecamp the product, but Basecamp the philosophy. 
  What is this software about? What is it <strong>not</strong> about?
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Basecamp is not about hard metrics</strong>. 
  It's not about &ldquo;why are so many things red&rdquo; or &ldquo;why is that number so high&rdquo; 
  or &ldquo;why is that line going down&rdquo;. Those things might tell you some contrived bad news.
  Let's trust that our customers are trying to do good work.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Basecamp is about momentum</strong>. Taking a meaningful step down the path today. Celebrating the progress you just made.
  Re-evaluating work from the vantage point now. Communication over calculation.
</p>
<p>
  The home screen should exude making you <em>feel good</em>. 
</p>
<p>
  In control.<br>
  In meaningful thought.<br>
  Calm.<br>
  Focused.<br>
  Productive.<br>
  Satisfied.<br>
</p>
<p>
  Nothing that the internet, AI, or social media seems to be about today.
</p>
<p>
  This was my North Star for the week. Making the Home screen not just a launching pad for everything else, 
  but feel like a home. A place that's inviting for the latest customer. A place a 10-year Basecamp customer 
  might look at in a new way.
</p>
<hr>
<h3>The Briefcase</h3>
<p>
  The old Home screen was about your projects, with some stuff about you at the bottom.
  This Home screen is about <strong>you</strong> first. The main area (which I'm calling "the briefcase" internally
  but doesn't have to be called anything on the app) shows you two sections.
</p>
<div class="figure-container smaller">
  <figure>
    <%= link_to image_tag("dd-og-site.webp", alt: "A screenshot of the original DoneDone marketing site"), "https://web.archive.org/web/20100927203150/http://www.getdonedone.com/index.aspx", target: "_blank", class: "link-thumbnail" %>
  </figure>
</div>
<h4>What's on tap</h4>
<p>
  This section consolidates your assigned to-dos, cards, events, and automatic check-ins across all your projects in one place,
  in the following order:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>If you've marked any assignments <em>Up Next</em>, they go at the top.</li>
  <li>Items due today (or have an end date of today) go next.</li>
  <li>After that, the next two days where you have something due.</li>
</ul>
<p class="note">
  <strong>Logic thoughts:</strong> I would show maybe 8 items at most. These would naturally go away as you check off to-dos or
  mark a card as "Done" or "Not Now", bringing the next items up. 
</p>
<p>
  Underneath, a button to more items on tap would expand the list, and a link to 
  your overdue assignments would link off to the "My assignments with dates" section of "My assignments" since
  overdue assignments show at the top of that page.
</p>
<p>
  Right underneath the "What's on tap" header is a short sentence: "Your upcoming assignments, events, and check-ins."
  The first two would link to "My assignments", "My schedule". (I don't believe there is a "My check-ins" page at the global level yet.)
  If this person isn't tied to any project with check-ins, we could omit that last part.
</p>
<p>
  For first time customers, we could stub the default "My Project" project with a sample to-do and event, and also turn on the 
  Card Table by default with a card. <%= link_to "Here's what that intro page would look like to a first time customer.", "/", target: "_blank" %>
</p>
<h4>Don&rsquo;t forget</h4>
<p>
  I love the "Don't forget" concept. It's a great way to curate all the other forms of communication in Basecamp regardless of where they come from. 
  I think that list should show up on the Briefcase as well. This way, the briefcase shows you:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    The items you're responsible for that are due at a certain time.
  </li>
  <li>
    The items that don't necessarily have a due date but are important to you.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  The Home screen now gives you a greater sense of control and calm. That an important thing hasn't slipped through the cracks. 
  You'd want to come here to make sure you didn't forget anything, and <%= link_to "an empty briefcase", "/", target: "_blank" %> should make you feel good too!
</p>
<hr>
<h3>A calm thought to start your day</h3>
<p>
  We all know the benefits of reading a few pages of a book before you go to bed instead of doom-scrolling through your phone. 
  But what about the reverse? What about reading a short, thought-provoking piece of non-fiction
  to rev up your brain in the morning before you hit that first task rather than...doom-scrolling through your phone?
</p>
<p>
  So, I thought it would be fun to surface one philosophical-thought-by-Basecamp each day. No algorithm. No random rotations.
  One thought a day that lives as a little sticky note at the bottom of the briefcase. (I originally had this at 
  the top but thought it might be too invasive.)
</p>
<p>
  For example, Jason's (probably) written hundreds of posts that could fit this daily dopamine hit.
