<hr>
<h3>Building on your day (stickers)</h3>
<p>
  This is not about stats. this is about feeling good. A step forward. A thing done. It's ephemeral. It resets daily.
</p>
<p>
  The usual experience of completing tasks in software isn't very motivating.
  You complete a task? It grays out.
  Drag a card to &ldquo;Done&rdquo;? It just goes away.
  Sign off your Zoom meeting? Crickets.
  [task,card,event,time-tracked]
</p>
<p>
  Everytime you get something done during the day, the Home screen should celebrate that in a Basecamp-y way. 
  Not with a small increment in a pie chart. Not confetti raining down from the top of the screen. Just a nudge. A wink.
  That's what this area is for. 
</p>
<p>
  To keep with the philosophy. these shouldn't be too calculated (besides time tracked). It's not &ldquo;you've completed 30% of your tasks today&rdquo;,
  it's more like &ldquo;hey, you got things done today!&rdquo;. Roll over the icons and they point you to relevant places in Basecamp
  for more detail (though later on we could perhaps build in a more tailored experience). That's enough. 
</p>
<p>
  Note: We wouldn't gray out and show here. If you have a to-do done the icon appears. If it doesn't you don't see something grayed out.
  This means if nothing gets done, there's no feeling of "I got nothing done". It may just not have been that type of day. 
</p>
<p>
  I konw you guys dont do "counts" but i do them for good things. counts on boosts and time tracked.
  Everything here is a positive. Put the numbers in!!!!!! Everything usually on upper right has a feeling of urgency and its red. so lets make it lower.
</p>
<p>
  If there are more 'things' to add later on perhaps we'd redesign. Perhaps make it even more randomized.
  Right now it is a nice 3 on 3 side to side where if you dont have everything its still ok. it looks normal.
  but i have a hunch tehre arent going to often be too many drastically new things.
</p>
<p>
  Stickers would also lead you to places you might not know about. All your boosts, your full timesheet, your assignmetsn, etc. 
</p>
<hr>
<h3>A single list of what's coming up</h3>
<p>
  Working your way down the Home screen, next up is what's coming up. 
</p>
<p>
  The current selling point is that Bascamp is one tool that covers the core features of other tools. But the flipside is it can
  feel like an umbrella of just a bunch of tools. Seeing how they all fit together takes some time.
</p>
<p>
  One of the learning curves with Basecamp is knowing where all the pieces live. There's to-dos and cards. There's chats, pings, 
  and messages. There's events. Automatic check-ins. They're all siloed in their own areas of the product. The home screen would
  also serve as a way to bring all the relevant, timely stuff in one place. Think of this area as your "Today" briefcase or backpack.
</p>
<p>
  I think this helps new folks understand how all the pieces fit together. On trial signup we could stub out a sample to-do, have
  the card table turned on automatically with a sample card, and a sample event. Make it clear they are samples (no need to try to 
  "fake them" as something real) but this way a new person doesn't feel overwhelmed.
</p>
<p>
  Ordering thoughts: All events on top, then all "Up next" you marked, then all Todos/cards due that day, then all to-dos with a date range still running-
  BTW i noticed a to-do can have a range of dates.... If NO date based things then maybe just pull any things?
</p>
<hr>
<h3>What about all the projects?</h3>
<p>
  This is one I debated awhile this week about. Seeing all your projects is still important. And right now, the clearest place to see them 
  is on the Home screen. I also imagine that for some folks, particularly managers, seeing projects is more important than 
  their own work. 
</p>
<p>
  For a one-week exercise, I thought we shouldn't touch projects at all, but instead have the projects UI come after my new work. 
  I like the stack option and re-arrangements. It's a pretty involved "thing". If you prefer to see htis then flip it. If not leave it below.
</p>
<hr>
<h3>A focus on one thing</h3>
<p>
  There are so many ways to get to other parts. All sorts of reports. Segregated by projects. Manual feels per project. 
  But no place that talks about you, regardless of the projects you're on, and curates
  what you've done, taking all the features into account.
</p>
